                    <item>
              <title>T1: Project Management Theme: The Role of the Change Manager</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/3552</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/3552</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p><strong><em>Session Overview</em></strong></p>
<p style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS--><em><strong><a href="http://www.jisc.ac.uk/media/documents/events/2010/07/the role of the change manager - ros penny.ppt" target="_blank">Open session slides in a new window</a></strong></em><strong><em><br /></em></strong></p>
<p>The role of the change manager in an Institution is often overlooked.&nbsp; The first part of this session will explore the importance of the role, how change agents within the institution can be identified and what it takes to be an effective change manager.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The second part of the session will comprise a real life example from the University of Derby where the students became the change agents during the rollout of the DERBI project <a href="http://www.derby.ac.uk/experience/jisc-enrolment-project">http://www.derby.ac.uk/experience/jisc-enrolment-project</a> .&nbsp; Sue Morrison and Jean Mutton will talk through the service design techniques and tools they used, how these can be applied across other areas within institutions and provide valuable insights into their successes and challenges.</p>
<p>There will be plenty of time for questions, thoughts and ideas in the third and final part.</p>
<p><strong><em>Session Chair</em></strong></p>
<p>Ros Penny - JISC - Director of Portfolios and Change Management</p>
<p><strong><em>Speakers</em></strong></p>
<p>Sue Morrison&nbsp;- Senior Assistant Registrar (Student Experience) - DERBI Project - University of Derby</p>
<p>Jean Mutton - Student Experience Project Manager&nbsp;- DERBI Project - University of Derby</p>
<p><strong><em>What can delegates expect to learn / gain / take away from the session?</em></strong></p>
<p>A greater understanding of what the role of the change manager entails and why it is so important to the successful implementation of new processes, systems and ways of working.</p>
<p><strong><em>Who should attend?</em></strong></p>
<p>Projects with new processes, systems or ways of working requiring rollout within their Institution.</p>
<p><strong><em>Room</em></strong></p>
<p>1-04</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Fri, 30 Jul 2010 14:23:40 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>T1: Project Management Theme: Project Management Methodologies – Agile and Prince 2 - making them work for you</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/3401</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/3401</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p><strong><em>Session Overview</em></strong></p>
<p>In the current cost-cutting climate, the success of projects is becoming paramount to the reputation and future funding provision for Institutions. The biggest risk to a project is lack of understanding of how to approach and manage the work or incorrect use of a methodology.&nbsp; This session explores the use of 2 methodologies, their benefits and the types of project for which they are appropriate.&nbsp; The session will include real life examples and an opportunity to discuss the issues facing you and your project.&nbsp; It will look at how adoption of elements of a methodology can vastly improve the success of your project.</p>
<p><strong><em>Session Chair</em></strong></p>
<p>Alistair Miles</p>
<p><strong><em>Speakers</em></strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Agile Methodology - David Flanders&nbsp;- JISC Programme Manager - Information Environment Team</li>
<li>Prince2 / Prince2 light - John Burke&nbsp;- JISC Infonet</li>
<li>Some general pitfalls of applying methodologies: Mark MacGillivray (odaesa</li>
<li>Agile Representatives: Ben Charlton (Shuffl, University of Kent); Tony Hirst, (jiscPRESS,&nbsp;Open University) ; Graham Klyne (Oxford University)</li>
<li>Prince2 Representatives: Len Tildsley&nbsp;(Shrewsbury College),&nbsp;Jonathan Day (Lancaster University)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong><em>What can delegates expect to learn / gain / take away from the session?</em></strong></p>
<p>This session will provide an overview of Agile and Prince2 methodologies (with real life examples) to allow delegates an insight into ways in which they can improve management of their projects. Project managers leave the session with a greater awareness of project management methodologies and the enthusiasm to follow up further using resources highlighted in the session &ndash; i.e. Infokit on Project Management and details on Agile.</p>
<p><strong><em>Who should attend?</em></strong></p>
<p>Delegates with an interest expanding their knowledge base&nbsp;of Project Management tools and&nbsp;methodologies and their practical application</p>
<p><strong><em>Room</em></strong></p>
<p>1-02 &amp; 1-03</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Fri, 30 Jul 2010 15:21:42 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>MASHe: Keynotes with Twitter subtitles</title>
