                    <item>
              <title>What is a Design Atelier? </title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2715</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2715</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>Prompted by an interesting discussion at a JISC Cluster Meeting I have created this cloud to explore further what a Design Atelier actually is?&nbsp;<br /><br /><strong>Background<br /></strong>The <a href="http://www.jisc.ac.uk/whatwedo/programmes/elearning/curriculumdelivery/atelierd.aspx">ATELIER-D</a> project takes as its starting point the centuries-old methods of learning and teaching in the studio of a master artist or craftsperson. The project brings the spirit of the atelier into the 21st century. It develops the notion of the &lsquo;virtual design studio&rsquo; using ICTs to create powerful learning and teaching environments.</p>
<p>&nbsp;In his keynote presentation at the OpenLearn conference&nbsp;30-31st October 2007 at The Open University (OU), John Seeley Brown used the term &lsquo;atelier&rsquo; to characterise an emerging form of learning and teaching based on social networks, a distinct participatory approach by learners and teachers and pedagogy rooted in practice. Seeley Brown drew on his experience in architecture education but many in the parent domain of design education will recognise the well-established and powerful approach offered by the atelier (see link below).<br /><br />As part of the JISC funded ATELIER-D project the OU are researching how a virtual atelier can be created using the latest Web 2.0 tools that support a wide range of distance learning designs students.<br /><strong><br />This cloud<br /></strong>This cloud seeks to promote discussion about what you think a Design Atelier is?</p>
<ul>
<li>What are the key attributes that make up a Design Atelier?&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>
<li>What makes it so special?</li>
<li>Is the nature of the physical space important?&nbsp; Should it be large and open or small&nbsp; and private?</li>
<li>What type of teaching methods should be used?</li>
<li>How can communication be used to support learning?&nbsp;</li>
</ul>
<p>This link&nbsp;below takes&nbsp;you to a short video clip to prompt the discussion. <br />Your thoughts and views are most welcome.</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Fri, 27 Nov 2009 17:41:28 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Keynote: Peter Bradwell: Becoming an Edgeless University</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2705</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2705</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>Peter argued that Universities current ways are working are not sustainable. He identified the challenges of Universities as:</p>
<ul>
<li>Maintaining standards</li>
<li>Rising demand and widening participatrion</li>
<li>Strained resources</li>
</ul>
<p>He suggested that in order to survive they need to become 'edgeless' and that technology can help with this, supporting collaboration, availability of information and people ie that technology is/ should be central to the way institutions provide learning and facilitate research.</p>
<p>In the second part of the keynote he suggests that Universities can embrace technologies in different ways in the move towards edgelessness - helping teachers teach and learners learn, communicating research and in thinking about ways of connecting with the world. He invited the audience to vote on the issues.</p>
<p><strong>Helping teachers teach and learners learn</strong></p>
<p><strong>Priorities</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Teaching students to analyse information and work collaboratively</li>
<li>Putting lecture notes, podcasts and videos on line</li>
<li>Providing more interative teaching</li>
<li>More online contact with students</li>
<li>Training staff and academics</li>
</ul>
<p>In a vote the audience of this keynote thought the first and last of these should be priorities.</p>
<p><strong>Inhibitors and challenges</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Staff skills and awareness</li>
<li>Staff engagement and willingness to learn</li>
<li>Lack of institutional interest or leadership</li>
<li>A lack of resources to invest</li>
<li>It's difficult to know what and when to change</li>
</ul>
<p>The audience said the 3rd of these most significant - if you get this right the rest will follow.</p>
<p><strong>Priorities</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Making research more freely available</li>
<li>'Curation' of research data</li>
<li>Openness with institutions' data</li>
<li>Promoting shared resources</li>
<li>Understanding researchers'/ academics' needs</li>
</ul>
<p>Promoting shared resources scored the most highly.</p>
<p><strong>Priorities</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>New more flxible degree courses</li>
<li>Links with alternative providers like School of Everything</li>
<li>More purely online provision</li>
<li>Collaboration between institutions</li>
<li>Staff training in supporting new kinds of learning</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Inhibitors and challenges</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The way formal education in funded mitigates against innovation</li>
<li>We don't know enough about what learners want</li>
<li>It's hard to balance online provision with face to face needs</li>
<li>Universities should retain the current models of teaching provision</li>
<li>maintaining a pursuit of 'widening participation'</li>
</ul>
<p>The first of these was considered fundemental by the voters.</p>
<p><strong>Catalysts for change</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Staff training and support</li>
<li>Supporting collaborative research platforms</li>
<li>A greater recognition of and status for high quality teaching</li>
<li>Understanding the value and role of your university</li>
<li>More resources dedicated to improving the use of technology</li>
</ul>
<p>Middle one scored higher than the others here.</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Thu, 26 Nov 2009 10:25:01 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Learner experiences of eLearning</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2693</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2693</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>From the website:</p>
<p><em>"The programme focussed on the learner voice. Learners allowed us into their worlds and showed us what it is like to study in a technology-rich age. The projects produced a huge collection of rich, detailed data that sheds light on what learners expect from the use of technology in post-compulsory education and the choices they make about using technology to support their study.</em></p>
<p><em>The research took a holistic approach to technology use. We were not so interested in how technology is used on one module, or in one part of the institution, as in how learners interact with technology throughout their learning lives.</em></p>
<p><em>The resources here will be of interest to teachers and staff supporting learning in post-16 education, researchers of student learning, e-learning developers, policy-makers and institutional managers. We intend for the assets in this site to be available to the education community for repurposing and reuse under a <a rel="nofollow" href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.0/uk/">Creative Commons licence<sup><img src="https://mw.brookes.ac.uk/images/icons/linkext7.gif" border="0" alt="" width="7" height="7" align="absmiddle" /></sup></a>."</em></p>
<p>Project website: <a href="https://mw.brookes.ac.uk/display/JISCle2/About">https://mw.brookes.ac.uk/display/JISCle2/About</a></p>]]></description>
